<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Matthew Parsons on behalf of Sirius Minerals Plc</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#14112c; font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt">EIS 10</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Matthew Parsons on behalf of Sirius Minerals Plc.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sirius Minerals welcomes the opportunity to submit written evidence to the inquiry.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sirius Minerals is a UK-listed, global potash development company. The York Potash Project, a proposal to build a new state-of-the-art potash mine near Whitby in North Yorkshire, is the company’s flagship project. It has the potential to help Sirius to bec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ome a leading global potash producer, significantly boost the UK economy, and put the UK at the forefront of the global mining industry in the approach to innovative mine design in sensitive landscapes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sirius has defined the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">world’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> largest highest and g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rade polyhalite resource in North Yorkshire. Polyhalite is a rare form of potash which uniquely contains four of the six macro-nutrients necessary for plant growth. As the world’s population expands and the land available for farming diminishes, balanced a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd sustainable fertilization using poyhalite is rapidly becoming regarded as an effective solution to global food security.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our evidence to the inquiry will focus on:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The vital role the extractives sector has in modern day society, and the key contributi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on it can make to addressing the national and global challenges we face</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The significant contribution of the sector to the UK economy</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The importance of ensuring there is a secure national supply of key minerals</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">How the sector can help to drive UK growth</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uring the skills and qualifications the sector requires are available in the labour market</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The importance of demonstrating a proactive commitment to the International Council on Mining and Metals Sustainable Development Principles </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the contributi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The extractives sector is central to the way we live our lives. Everything we see around us is made of materials that were either grown or mined. The places we live and work, how we travel, the tech</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nology we all rely upon, and the food we eat are all dependent on the extractives sector. As a result it is one of the oldest and largest industries in the world.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Extractive industries make a significant contribution to the UK economy, both directly and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hrough supporting other key sectors such as construction, manufacturing, energy and agriculture. The value of the sector to the UK economy is estimated to be as much as £10 billion.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The York Potash Project can make a significant contribution to the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">economy. In addition to creating thousands of jobs, an independent socio-economic study has calculated that the project can, at full production:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Strengthen the UK fiscal position by generating over £300 million a year in tax receipts</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Make an annual contrib</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ution to the national economy of up to £1.4 billion, representing up to 0.10% of GDP growth</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Contribute to reducing the UK Current Account Deficit by up to 10%  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How does the UK based extractive industries support employment a) in the UK and b) for UK citi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">zens overseas?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Around 70,000 people are employed by the extractive industries in the UK, and many thousands more in the sectors it supports. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The York Potash Project will create up to 1000 new, skilled and sustainable jobs, and approximately 2000 further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> opportunities in the supply chain in a local economy with historic low employment growth.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK has some of the most highly regarded mining consultancies, which are in high demand worldwide. The UK still produces good quality engineers and geologists th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at are highly sought after </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the global labour market. There is however, an increasing national and global shortage of the skills the extractives sector requires. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Does UK industry benefit more widely from the UK’s position as a centre for extractive in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">dustries i.e. In sales of machinery and services to international businesses in the sector?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Yes, mining equipment is manufactured</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the UK which supplies the national</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and wider global market, and supports the UK manufacturing base. Joy Global, a world le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ader in mining machinery and services, has three UK-based manufacturing facilities. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Does the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">as shale gas?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is well known within the extractives sector that there is a national and global shortage of people with the skills required. This is also the case with other sectors requiring similar skill sets, such as advanced manufacturing. The UK is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not producing enough people with technical skills and qualifications.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK extractives sector is a dynamic, technology-driven industry requiring Level 3 and higher level Science Technology Engineering and Maths (STEM) qualifications, particularly engine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ers and skilled technicians.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK Commission for Employment and Skills forecast a demand for around 1.9 million workers with engineering skills up to 2020, of which almost 90% are replacement jobs as the existing workforce retires. This equates to over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">87,000 new workers each year qualified to Level 4+ and 69,000 qualified to Level 3.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">42% of employers requiring STEM skills have difficulties recruiting. The UK produces less than half number of required engineers at Level 4 and less than 40% at Level 3. A low participation rate in STEM subjects at Key Stage 4 is a key part of the problem.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In 2009/10 just 16% of entrants achieved GCSEs at A*-C in 3 Sciences and Maths (vital for progression to A levels) and only 56% of schools entered pupils for ‘triple Science’ GCSEs.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sirius Minerals recognises this issue and the challenge we face in reali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sing our commitment to maximising local employment in the York Potash Project. The Company is continuing to invest in an education and skills programme that ensures the right skills are available in the local area. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the impact of the industry of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he UK signing up to the EITI?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sirius Minerals is committed to the principle of good corporate citizenship and supports the EITI.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition from elsewhere or can it be used to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> make the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Company has committed to the ICMM sustainable development principles. In general increased regulation should be discouraged.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the competitive landscape for the ext</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Having a secure supply of critical minerals is in the national interest. We recommend that the Government develops a UK minerals strategy as part of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the overall Industrial Strategy. This should have the dual aim of ensuring that we have access to minerals of national importance, and that economic growth is generated by exploiting our own indigenous supply. This will enable the UK to reduce a re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">liance o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n imports, and drive</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK economic growth through exports to the global market. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#14112d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>